default3) Public Purposes:
defaultThe fifth of the BBC's Public Purposes as defined in its Charter and Agreement is that of "Bringing the UK to the world and the world to the UK". The BBC Trust's interpretation of that remit includes a commitment to "build a global understanding on international issues". 
defaultWith regard to the Arab-Israeli conflict, the BBC consistently 
defaultneglects
default to inform its audiences of the scale of terror threats facing Israeli civilians. It frequently ignores incidents of missile fire at civilian targets and 
defaultother
default terror attacks against them. It downplays the subject of Palestinian terrorism in general and has erroneously portrayed imprisoned terrorists as 'political prisoners' – see 
defaulthere
default and 
defaulthere
default.
defaultThe BBC's 
defaultrepresentation
default of the subject of the Middle East peace process is frequently 
defaultindistinguishable
default from that of the Palestinian Authority, with disproportionate – and 
defaultfrequently inaccurate
default - emphasis on factors promoted by the PA as 'obstacles to peace'. At the same time, factors no less relevant to the peace process such as the Hamas/Fatah split, Palestinian terrorism, official PA incitement and glorification of terror and Israeli security 
defaultconcerns are given considerably less coverage, thereby hampering audience understanding of the issue. 
defaultBBC reporting from the areas controlled by the 
defaultPalestinian Authority
default and Hamas is notable for its consistent avoidance of issues such as the oppression of minorities, women's rights, government corruption and the lack of press freedom. 
defaultRemarkable too is the sheer scale of BBC reporting on Israel. Over the past nine months (
defaultMarch to November 2013 inclusive
default), Israel has consistently been in the top five Middle East countries receiving the most coverage on the BBC News website, despite the fact that much of the rest of the region continues to be plagued by political and military turmoil. 
defaultOne particularly 
defaultworrying
default characteristic of the BBC's Middle East reporting has been its tendency to promote unchallenged conspiracy theories and propaganda produced by repressive regimes to worldwide audiences – see examples 
